animal.description:
Lisa / Female / 1 Year / 34 lbs / Aussie Mix / Toronto

Meet Lisa! Lisa can make anyone's heart melt when she rests her head in your lap for attention. If you happen to stop petting her - she will offer her paw and gently encourage you to continue. Her fosters say she is 95% a sweet little angel and 5% a tornado. When she gets the zoomies, look out! She becomes a whirling ball of energy and playful excitement, sucking everything she can grab into her vortex of temporary chaos! Overall Lisa is gentle, affectionate, sensitive, quiet, loyal and eager to please her people. Lisa will make the ultimate companion to an active family who shares her love of fun!

With people she knows or has met before, Lisa is affectionate and wants attention right away. She can be mouthy and demand your focus at times. She has no sensitivities around her body and likes to be touched everywhere! With new people she can be hesitant and prefers to observe from a distance. Eventually, her curiosity will draw her close enough for a sniff. If strangers try to pet her before she is ready, she will back away. Proper, respectful introductions, space and time are key to winning Lisa’s trust. Lisa is very timid around loud or unexpected noises, she startles easily and will bolt and hide. She is only looking for homes without children under the age of 14.

When left alone Lisa is crated and settles right away. She loves her crate and has no problem hanging out in there. She has only been tested for short periods, so if transitioning her to a regular schedule she will need adjustment. She is currently getting 2-3 long walks a day and has been successful with this schedule. With consistent opportunities to use the washroom, Lisa is fully potty trained.

True to her breed, Lisa is higher energy and needs more stimulation than your average dog. She has some typical Aussie instincts and can be mouthy or nippy when she is seeking approval or attention. She will jump all over her humans if given the chance and if it is not corrected, she becomes even more excitable. Adopters should be prepared to provide extensive mental stimulation, and keep outdoor walks structured. Lisa would likely benefit from having a “job” outside like carrying a backpack. She is very sensitive and empathetic and may yowl when she hears sirens outside.

Lisa is smart and eager to learn commands. She has quickly learned sit, lie down, focus, crate when asked, and come is a work in progress. She is learning to walk on leash but she still pulls a lot. Her progress so far has been excellent, and she is very responsive to gentle guidance. She has a high prey drive and is extremely sensitive to sounds. She wants to explore everything but will also stop suddenly to take in her surroundings. Adopters should have some experience with leash training and be confident redirecting as needed.

Lisa’s ideal family would live in a house, with a fully fenced back yard. She would love the opportunity to run freely, but can’t be trusted in an unsecured space yet. She may be able to adapt to the city, but would prefer to leave in a quiet or suburban area. She is best suited for country living with lots of space to live her dreams. Lisa has not been officially tested with dogs or cats.

If you’re interested in adopting Lisa please apply at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/adoption-info#adoption-form

Lisa’s adoption fee is $700. To learn more about our adoption fees and the adoption process, please visit our FAQs at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/about-us#about-faqs.

animal.description:
Miss Maggie came to Critter Cavalry malnourished, shy and unsure of herself, but with a heart of gold. Though we dont know her background, we know it was heartbreaking. She is deathly afraid to be in a home without another dog. If she has that familiar furry friend that she can trust, she will feed off their lead and become the sweetest cuddlebug ever! Without that companion, though she shies at the slightest noise, movement or even shadow and as such must have a home with another dog. She has been around all kinds of dogs, from puppies to seniors big and small and loves them all and seems to have no concern about cats. She makes friends wherever she goes. Everyone she meets either describes her as 'sweetheart' or 'love' and she certainly is both! After she begins to trust - which is no time if there's a dog around - she will climb all over you and mouth and lick and wiggle from head to toe and absolutely loves being with her people - especially if they're on the couch or bed. She has an amazing red ticked coat, expressive golden eyes and the cutest 'yoda' ears guaranteed to melt your heart!

Maggie's an interesting 1 to 2 year old Cattle dog mix - short and stocky and loves to use her oversized puppy paws to bat at her new friends. Don't let her small stature fool you, though, she has energy for days and adores running around 'pretending' to chase a toy... She's always the fastest one to it, but frequently prefers to let the other dogs get the toy so she can 'herd' them in using that cattle dog nature. If she even thinks it's about to be playtime she starts hopping and barking - ready to run! She's now healthy, housebroken and learning basic manners quickly and just needs a loving forever home that will teach her to trust again. This girl is a love.needs a fenced yard for sure and another dog for the long haul.

Her love of dogs is insane and she really has been amazing with every one we've come across regardless of age, attitude, gender, size, etc- and we've been around dozens this month!!! She is interesting with new humans, though.... she just doesnt know what to think of us! She's another special little lady for sure though :) If you are interested in a second companion dog that will love to the moon and back please email us at: ccrtennessee@gmail.com

ADOPTION FEE REQUIRED. Contact ccrtennessee@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Scooter Eugene loves you already and you've only just met through a photo! Scooter is a perfect, laid-back, and intelligent senior gentleman, and is SO happy to just snuggle (and play ball of course).

Scooter was surrendered when his family was no longer able to care for him, so he has a lot of experience in a family environment. His interests include: treats, napping, and his ball! Though Scooter may be 12 years old, you wouldn't know it when the ball comes out! Scooter does enjoy fetch, but also loves just batting his giant ball around and entertaining himself.

Scooter doesn't have any negative traits to speak of. He has loved every human and dog he's met. Potential forever homes must know that he does have a partially prolapsed rectum, and a heart murmur - both have been checked by a vet - neither of which are detrimental or affect him at all in his daily life.

Scooter would thrive in a home that allows for naps, as well as would play ball with him daily (ball is life). It would be excellent if he wasn't left alone for long periods of time, as he enjoys his jaunts around the yard every 4 hours or so. He is potty-trained as long as he can get out in that time frame. He is also crate-trained.

Scooter weighs about 23 lb, is neutered, microchipped, UTD on vaccines and heartworm negative and on prevention.

Scooter can't wait to show you his goofy personality, and his favorite ball! Once you meet him, you'll no doubt fall in love!

To find out more about Scooter Eugene, contact his foster mom, Brittany, at brittany.hutchins18@yahoo.com or text only to 802-752-5683. His adoption fee is $225. He is fostered in eastern North Carolina.
Please use the foster momma or dad's contact information above for questions.
The process always begins with an application which can be found at The Boston Terrier Rescue of East Tennessee website
Note that in most cases, we do not adopt to families with small children, e.g., 'under 6,' as a precaution to the child's safety and the dog's safety. In some cases with larger Boston mixes or other dogs, we do make exceptions. Please ask the foster momma.
We prefer to place dogs within driving distance of where they are being fostered. If someone from outside the local area is approved for adoption, they must be willing to personally drive/fly to get the dog. The East Coast division (NC/SC/VA/MD/DC) does have special transport capabilties for their kids. Ask them.
Also, submission of an application and fee does not guarantee adoption of any specific Boston since that particular dog may have applications pending or may not be the right match for you.

animal.description:
Meet Comet, a 3 year old Great Pyrenees looking for his forever home. Comet was rescued from an old/abandoned junk yard located in the Eastern foothills of the Appalachian mountains. He was severely malnourished and missing much of his beautiful fur.  Through rescue and an amazing and committed foster family, he is making wonderful progress in every way. 

Comet is a "gentle giant" and commensurate with his breed, is a guardian of his kingdom.  He loves to be loved. He will nuzzle, lift his paw up to get your attention, and walk in synchronicity with you. He has a zen-like energy about him. However, he carries a trait to be independent and GUARD, patrolling day or night. He likes to use his giant size and booming bark at any sights and sounds, or just because. He settles down once he knows everything is safe and secure. He is an intuitive, independent thinker and formidable protector.

With continued positive reinforcement, Comet was able to be introduced and integrated with the smaller resident dogs. However, it is always with supervision when they are together.

Comet's new family must have a fully and sturdy fenced in yard. We will give preference to families with Great Pyr experience because he certainly is representative of the breed! Absolutely no small kids - 15+ only. Owners with resident dogs must understand slow introduction and integration. We will provide training assistance with his adoption. 

The adoption fee of $400 will include spay/neuter, microchip, age appropriate/required vaccinations, treatment for heartworm and any other necessary medical treatment to assure a healthy new pup for your family.


IMPORTANT DISCLAIMER: Although we do our best to describe breed, since our pups all come from shelters we can not and will not make any guarantee on breed or size. We can tell you that they are 100% RESCUED! And that is the BEST breed!

If you are interested in adopting/meeting , please visit our website at www.starfishanimalrescue.com or you may complete the online adoption application on our Facebook Page https://www.facebook.com/starfishanimalrescue/app/134425496630143/?ref=page_internal Once you complete and submit your dog adoption application we will set up an appointment to meet this pup!

animal.description:
ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS
Fenced yard

My name is Thor. I am a Chihuahua/ Beagle mix looking for a new home. My person was no longer able to care for me so I went to this great foster home until I could find a new family. I am the perfect combination of my breeds. Not to say that I am perfect because if you know either breed you know that's not true but I am a good boy. I look like a Chi and sound like a beagle on the rare occasion that I have reason to bark. I am a complete lap dog and love to sleep curled up with my foster mom. I am pretty low energy so I don't need much activity to be happy. Going for walks sometimes would be nice but as long as I have a fenced yard I'm good. There are 2 things that make me mad. I do not like to be woken up suddenly if I am asleep and if my foster siblings crowd me too much I will get grumpy. For this reason I would be good as an only dog and in a home without kids. When I am made I might bite which is typical Chihuahua. My foster mom knows just to leave me alone until I am nice again. Thankfully this doesn't happen very often. I am about 2 years old and weigh appx 10lbs.

If you would like to meet Thor send us an email to theloveofk9s@yahoo.com and we will get back with you as soon a we can.

Adoption donation pays for all vetting...neuter, a heart worm test, all vaccinations, deworming, flea prevention, a microchip and a wellness exam.

animal.description:
Meet Cobra Kai! This pup is ½ Cane Corso, ½ Pit bull, and 100% a handsome devil. This giant boy is about 70 pounds and 7 months old (as of 1/28/21). The Cobra Kai way (referencing the great Karate Kid movies and comeback show) is: STRIKE FIRST, STRIKE HARD, NO MERCY! And our boy came with that motto ingrained in his brains. He lives for snuggles and scratchies, he loves to prance around and play, but he also enjoys finding all sorts of ways to keep us on our toes! 

He can snuggle next to you on the couch for hours while you nap; or you can wake up to a hole in his dog bed with chunks of foam covering the floor. He can keep himself entertained with his toys and stay on his spot like a good boy while you leave the room; or you can be gone for 2 minutes and return to a pulverized xbox remote. He likes to mix it up. 

Kai was surrendered to our vet at just 2 weeks old due an umbilical abscess. After surgery and a couple days in the hospital, he was taken home and bottle raised in foster care. Bottle puppies can struggle to develop normal social and emotional behaviors without their siblings and mother around. Kai started showing aggressive behaviors around 6-8wks old - protecting his toys, growling when disturbed, excessive mouthing, and other behaviors that may be understandable in some settings, but quite concerning for a young puppy. 

As a rescue, we elected to keep him (not post him for adoption) and continue his positive behavior training until his behaviors could become more predictable/controlled/stable. The last thing we'd want is for him to be adopted with mild behaviors, those behaviors intensify with a well-meaning but incapable home, and then he return unadaptable with intense and ingrained challenging behaviors. We feel that he's finally at a place where the right person(s) could take over from here and help him blossom into the squishy love-muffin he's meant to be! 

Through months of positive behavior training, Kai has become much more comfortable with - and often even looks forward to - people taking his bones and toys and tolerant of us messing with him whenever and wherever. He also continues to become less mouthy and develop more and more self control. He's definitely not perfect and since he's a dog, he never will be. His training will absolutely need to continue, especially as he matures throughout the next couple years. 

Kai currently lives well with 3 cats and 2 dogs and has had a several dog friends in the past. However, Kai is quite keen on cat chasing and has developed an large issue with meeting other dogs. Kai's cat chasing is currently easily curbed with a "leave it!" or a "come!" command. BUT, the behavior would need to be continually worked on and never tolerated nor trusted, or more simply, no cats allowed. 

Kai recently started lunging and barking angrily whenever he sees another dog. He does well with his foster siblings - a chihuahua and a pit bull, and had several dog friends of all sizes as a younger pup, but otherwise he hadn't met any dog friends over the last couple months. When we tried to introduce him to a dog friend last week, he started with lunging and barking and couldn't settle down to even officially meet. We've back-tracked a bunch to "below his threshold" to start working with him on this, but this is a big new behavior that will need to be continually worked with by us and then his future adopters. 

Kai has so much potential and he wants so hard to be a good boy. He'll need a very committed home dedicated to continuing his positive-behavior training and helping him be the bestest boy he can be. For further information about adopting Kai, please email MFdogadoptions@gmail.com or go to our website at MFdogrescue.org. Adoption application and approval required. We have an adoption fee of $350 which covers a small portion of Kai's medical expenses covered by the rescue. Kai is located in Christiansburg, VA.

animal.description:
Lady Lou is a 3 yrs old 25 lb Jack Russel Mix

Lady Lou is currently located in South Texas and will be transported to the Pacific Northwest.

Hello they call me Lady Lou, I don’t have your typical family love story, but with your help my meager beginning can have the best final chapters ever.  I lived on the streets so I am still learning the ropes as a posh house pet.  I am working on potty training but still have accidents, I know I will get the hang of it though.  I have been learning all about the leash and it’s not so bad, I do enjoy long walks.  I love playing with other dogs and I sometimes do not want them to stop when they want too so I tend to try to push them if they want rest before me.  I love people and I have been introduced to the wonders called your bed, I love to sleep with you but be careful if you leave me unattended the pillows sometimes explode, I don’t know how it happens but it’s really fun.  If you are ready for fun and adventure and to learn with me along the way I’m your Lady as the name says, please consider me for your furever family member.

Our organization only adopts within the United States.

Faith and Hope is a multi-state rescue with locations in Texas, Washington and Oregon. All dogs are rescued from the state of Texas to and transported to our Washington and Oregon locations with placement in their adoptive families. Our $425 adoption fee includes all core vaccinations (DHPP, rabies, spay/neuter, microchip)

If interested in learning more, please email us at faithandhopeadoptions@gmail.com or fill out our online application.

https://www.faithandhopefoundation.org/adoptionapp

If interested in learning more about our adoptable dogs and adoption process, or our foster home program, please contact us at above email.

Due to the number of requests that we receive on our puppies and dogs, please be advised that all adoption applications are processed in the order received. Once we send you an application, your place in line does not get reserved until your application is returned to us.

animal.description:
Huey / Male / 2 Years / 56 lbs / Hound Mix / Toronto

Meet Huey! Huey is as friendly as they come - he wants to be pet by everyone. When he wants attention he will follow his people around and paw for attention. As much as he loves to be near his people, he loves playing with dogs even more! He is described as playful, active, friendly, loving, smart and curious. Huey would do best with an active family who shares his love of socializing and outdoor adventure!

Huey is a total gentleman and greets his family by sitting for attention and pets. He even greets the concierge of their building because he knows there’s a head rub waiting for him! Huey wants to sniff everyone, and may pull to introduce himself. His foster family is trying to establish boundaries by teaching him that not everyone wants to be sniffed. Even though he loves affection, Huey likes to decide when he gets it. He has a threshold and will remove himself when he has had enough. His crate is his decompression spot and he feels safest in there. He is a very sensitive boy and does not appreciate being grabbed or hugged, so he is only looking for homes with kids ages 10+. Any children should be dog savvy and understand when to give him a break.

Huey has heart worm and is currently receiving treatment for it. Part of his recovery has meant he’s been primarily on bed rest in foster care. His activity is to remain low until his treatment is complete. This means keeping him calm, and offering controlled access to toys and play time. Walks should be kept slow and short for the time being all while keeping a close eye on his excitement level. He will need adopters committed to providing mental stimulation throughout the day to drain excess energy. In June of 2021, he will need a HW retest to confirm if treatment has been successful.

When left alone Huey is crated and settles very quickly. He may resist at first but with a small treat he generally goes in without issue. As long as he’s had enough exercise, he will sleep while left alone. On leash Huey pulls a lot and he is very strong. He is most excitable at the beginning of a walk when he is over stimulated and eager to explore every tree. True to the hound in him, he will follow his nose wherever it takes him. Leash etiquette will be an ongoing part of his training once he is able to go on full walks again.

Huey is smart, but extremely stubborn. If you don’t have a high value treat that motivates him, there’s a good chance he will go deaf. He knows sit and his foster family is trying to teach him to do so before and after he enters their home. He wants to take off and will fire through doors like a bullet if you let him. For his safety it will be very important that this structure continues in his forever home.

Huey’s ideal home would be a house with a fully fenced backyard. He is used to spending lots of time outdoors and would appreciate the space to run freely once he is off reduced activity. He could adapt to an apartment as long as his family is very active and can meet his needs. He will need adopters that in the mean time, understand his physical restrictions. Huey would do best with a family who has some dog experience and at least one other playful dog in the home. Huey would prefer homes outside of the city.

If you’re interested in adopting Huey please apply at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/adoption-info#adoption-form

Huey’s adoption fee is $800. To learn more about our adoption fees and the adoption process, please visit our FAQs at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/about-us#about-faqs.

animal.description:
In June of 2020, our Cruelty Investigator picked up a thin dog with no fur at all. We can’t imagine the pain poor Lily must have been in for so long; just touching her skin made it bleed. She was covered in scabs, bright pink and had many infected areas of her skin. While she had very little energy, Lily was a survivor, and has been working hard on her health over these past 7 months. She is finally ready to find her forever family and begin moving on from her difficult first few years of life.  

Currently in a foster home that reports Lily is a “huge source of joy and amusement” this shy but sweet girl is flourishing. She is well on her way to being potty and crate trained. She hasn’t had an accident in her foster home in weeks, and goes easily into her crate but does bark for a few minutes before settling down. Lily enjoys snuggling, chewing on hard bones and now has the energy for going on long walks. 

Lily has played with other dogs and very much enjoys wrestling and rumbling hard, so much so that she can find it hard to stop playing when other dogs are around! She would do well in an only dog home, or in a home with other dogs who enjoy a good hard romp and humans who could be proactive in reinforcing calm behavior when everyone is together. 

Lily is around 3 years old, weighs 65 lbs, is heartworm positive and has not yet been spayed. As a big girl who can occasionally be jumpy mouthy when excited she is looking for a home without children under 12 years of age. Having an intact animal in your home is an added responsibility that potential adopters should consider. She has been vaccinated, microchipped, and is current on parasite prevention.
Because of the long road to recover that Lily is still on, she is being offered as a foster to adopt candidate. This comes with many benefits such as access to our dog trainer and clinic, for Lily’s needs! The Tulsa SPCA will continue to treat Lily medically until she is healthy enough to be spayed, after which the adoption will be finalized. We will also soon begin treatment for her heartworms, at no cost to her adopter.  

Let us know if you are Lily’s happily ever after! 

HOW TO ADOPT
The Tulsa SPCA is currently operating on an appointment-only basis.
- Click on the orange "Interested in this animal? Click here!" button to apply to adopt.
- If you're approved, we'll contact you to finalize the paperwork, collect payment and arrange an appointment for your drive-thru adoption.
- Please stay home if you feel unwell, especially if you are experiencing symptoms of fever, cough or sore throat.
Thank you for your patience and understanding during this time. These policies may change as the Tulsa SPCA makes adjustments in response to the ongoing situation.

animal.description:
*do not call to inquiry about these puppies, read this post, and follow the instructions at the bottom*

In order to ensure your receive our follow up email, please add adopt@californiabullyrescue.org to your inbox contacts or check your spam folders

This litter was born on November  26th 2020 - their mother was saved a forced abortion 3 days before she was due to give birth. The shelter was going to spay her while she was pregnant and terminate pregnancy.

Applications for adoption are OFFICIALLY open for 7 days. Please read through and click the link at the bottom of this post for the application. If instructions aren’t followed, it’s possible you’ll miss the opportunity to adopt a pup.
•
Things to keep in mind:
1. Adopters will be required to purchase a training package from an approved (by us) balanced trainer.

2. Puppies will be spayed/neutered at 20 weeks, we will not make exceptions unless there is a medical reason that the dog cannot be put under for spay/neuter. No, we won’t wait till 1 year - Yes, we are aware of *possible* adverse growth affects of spaying/neutering young. Our concern is liability and avoiding accidental pregnancy. If you’re concerned about our spay/neuter policy, there are hundreds of other rescues that you can adopt from :)

3. The adoption process is lengthy, after you submit your application you will receive a follow up email within 10 days either with the next steps or advising we are declining to move forward. Please do not call/email within those 10 days advising you haven’t heard from us. If you haven’t heard from us by 10 days, feel free to email. As a reminder, every single person in our rescue is a volunteer. Once you submit the application you should get confirmation that it was submitted, if you didn’t receive confirmation then the application wasn’t submitted.

4. Puppies (or dogs) are NOT adopted out on a “first come, first serve” basis. They are adopted out by best fit - which is at our discretion.

5. We will not be accepting out of state adoptions at this time.

6. It would be HIGHLY beneficial to follow our Instagram: (@californiabullyrescue) to understand our mission and our policies/stances on: training, training tools, flex leashes, crate training, harnesses, dog parks, INSURANCE, multi-dog households, etc.

Adoption fee for puppies are $500 - they will have all medical taken care of (multiple sets of vaccinations, deworming, spay/neuter, microchip, rabies) and they’ve already started participating in training with our trainer. 

There are 4 boys, 1 girl.

animal.description:
Bebop came to us with his littermates and mom from Hamilton County. He and his littermates were small and a little sickly, but they grew into great little piggies! Bebop's siblings were adopted, but Bebop was held back as he appears to be complete deaf, and potentially has some vision impairment. He's been in a foster home working on some basic sign language, and gaining confidence. He will need to go to a home with at least one dog who is tolerant of puppies, especially those who might get startled while sleeping. He is very active and has two speeds - on and off! He absolutely relies on the other dogs in the home for cues to come when it's too far for him to see his hand signals. He would love a forever home who is familiar with deaf dogs and the safety concerns due to their deafness. He is otherwise completely perfect and loves to cuddle with his person and dogs!

Please visit our website at faithfulfriendsrescue.org/adoptable-pets if you are interested in adopting.

I am a mixed breed dog. This means I don't have a specific recognizable breed. The rescue uses the following guide which are guesses based on my current size and age for how big I will be when full grown: Mixed Breed (small) up to 25 pounds - Mixed Breed (medium) between 25-45 pounds - Mixed Breed (large) more than 50 pounds. For more information on, please visit the website https://faithfulfriendsrescue.org/adoptable-pets.

We are setting up adoptions with approved adopters on an appointment basis. We are no longer hosting adoption events at PetSmart until further notice. We are not arranging meet and greets; but appointments to finalize adoptions to limit exposure for all. Our adoptions come with a one week trial period in which if things are not working out, we will refund your adoption fee if you decide to return your newly adopted Faithful Friend. Our adoptions must be done in person and we do not arrange transport to adopters. Our adoption fees vary and we are only able to accept payments by card* at this time but include spay/neuter, heartworm test (dogs), FeLV/FIV test (cats), age appropriate vaccines and deworming, flea, tick and heartworm medication and microchip.

animal.description:
Apollo is new to our shelter.  He is a one-year-old male who was surrendered to us by his previous family.  It is our understanding that Apollo was too high energy for them.

This is likely the case of a young dog needing more exercise.  It is our experience that many young dogs end up in shelters when their activity needs do not match their current family situation or lifestyle.  Given the right amount of attention, exercise, and healthy stimulation, we find that these so-called "hyper" dogs transform very quickly and positively into well-balanced, calm dogs.

We are looking for an active family for Apollo.  He will thrive with a healthy outlet for his pent-up energy.  Email us for a pre-adoption questionnaire.  woof@slvaws.org

Once you are pre-approved for adoption, you may schedule an appointment to meet Apollo.

Are you looking for a dynamic duo? Double the trouble? Bonded besties? Here we are. 
I'm Laverne. I will get this out of the way first, I LOVE TREATS. With that being said, I'm on something humans call a diet (insert eye roll here). Shirley, my bestie, is more of a play ball kind of girl which is great if you're into that kind of thing! I'm sort of what they call Shirley's therapy dog, so we must be adopted together. That's okay though, after all that IS why you have 2 hands! We BOTH love a good scratch and belly rub! I do well in the car. I do well in my crate and I love my soft comfy doggy bed to sleep in at night! I do enjoy the company of my human friends too, so a good cuddle isn't out of the question!

animal.description:
Early on a cold rainy morning, our shelter manager was shocked to find Casper tied to the shelter back door.  Frightened and shivering, this poor dog had been abandoned sometime during the night without any protection from the elements.  He was very happy and relieved to finally be safe and warm.  From his physical condition, it was obvious Casper had been neglected.  He was covered in fleas and his skin had a nasty yeast infection.  After a quick trip to our vet, Casper was soon on the road to recovery.  
Casper is a snow-white, male Boxer mix estimated to be around three years old.  He is a large dog and underweight at fifty-five pounds.  This droopy-faced boy is very sweet, friendly and gentle.  He gives the best sloppy kisses!  Hard to understand why anyone would have treated him so bad.  Casper will make a wonderful family pet.  He loves people of all sizes and is friendly with other dogs.  We have not had him around cats but can test that for you.  Casper walks well on a leash and sits quietly on car rides.  He is always a gentleman and very obedient and cooperative.  We don’t know if Casper is completely housebroken but he does prefer going on grass.  A fenced in yard is a must to keep him safe when outside.  This special dog deserves a wonderful forever home.  Will you make Casper’s “happy-ever-after” dreams come true?  


To adopt this pet, Click "More About Us" and then "Adoption Application" to be directed to our online HSNWGA application form.  You will be contacted by our Adoption Coordinator once your application is reviewed and approved.  Due to high volume of applications, we are only able to contact those applicants that best meet the needs of that individual pet.

animal.description:
Meet sweet and spunky Cypress from down South! Cypress is a stunning, 2-3 year old mix (pit bull? lab? hound? shepherd?) who can do it all. She has the youthful energy of a younger dog (loves long walks, hikes, and fetching sticks) but she also totally falls in love with her people, and will just want to snuggle by your side. 

Cypress loves to play, and would do well as an only dog, or with another dog who could tolerate her playful antics after they have been properly introduced to each other. Cypress has also happily been around dog-savvy cats, again with proper introductions. She's a strong and bouncy girl, so would likely do best around kids 12 and up. 

Cypress was abandoned in a crate on the side of the road strewn with trash, and she'll need a family that will help her ease into being a dog surrounded by love and safety. She's such a quick learner (fully potty trained, knows sit and stay!) and she just wants to please her humans, so training will be so rewarding. Cypress's forever family must be willing to put in the time to improve her leash manners and turn her into the confident dog she hasn't had the chance to be ... yet!

If you're looking for a walking, hiking, jogging buddy that will also crash on the couch and adore you, Cypress is the girl for you.


Name: Cypress
Breed: Terrier/Retriever
Sex: Female
Age: Approx 1 year
Weight: 50 lbs 
Spayed/Neutered: Yes
Vaccinations: Up to date
Heartworm: Negative
Microchipped: Yes

BASED ON OUR OBSERVATIONS:
Good with Children: Over 12 (not formally tested with smaller children)
Good with Dogs: Yes, with dogs that match her high energy
Good with Cats: Yes, dog savvy

Adoption Fee: $475.00



IMPORTANT INFORMATION:
Interested in a specific dog, please fill out an application if you are interested in a dog. The number of individual inquiries is overwhelming and we are finding it difficult to respond to each one. We cannot guarantee you will receive a timely response.


Paws New England is a rescue, not a shelter, and as such we do not have our dogs housed in one location - they are in foster homes both in New England and in our southern foster homes. If you're interested in a specific dog, please complete a short online application and you will receive a reply within 48 hours so you can ask questions.


At present, if a dog is listed on our website, the dog is considered still available HOWEVER, may have applications that have come in before yours but it's still too early to know if any are a good match; therefore we encourage you to apply.




NOTICE WITH REGARD TO LOCATION OF DOGS: Please note: Paws New England is a foster-based rescue. We do not have a brick and mortar building to house the dogs we rescue. We have found that dogs in foster homes are much more adoptable because they have been observed in a home setting. Dogs listed with Paws New England typically reside in various locations throughout the south (primarily Tennessee, Texas, and Arkansas) and New England (not necessarily in the state of Rhode Island). You will be notified by the adoption coordinator of the location of the dog you are interested in so you have the ability to decide whether to pursue adoption or not.

Dogs transported to New England are done so at a fee of $150.00 paid directly to the transporting company by Paws New England; no additional transport costs are responsibility of adopter. This fee is included in the adoption donation.

Adoption donations cover pre-adoption vet costs (including vaccinations, spay/neuter when age appropriate, and heartworm testing/treatment when necessary), a microchip, and transportation to New England if necessary.

Donations for our young, healthy puppies and dogs support their fellow canines of advanced age or suffering from injuries and abuse whose donations are reduced but whose veterinary costs are typically much higher. We appreciate your understanding that your dog will help others in need.

All known information about the animal is listed above. We do our best to give accurate information, but most of our dogs are rescues and do not come with a known history.

Paws New England abides by the dog importation regulations set forth in the states of MA, CT, NH and RI.

animal.description:
MY NAME IS:  Dodge
POSTED TO PETFINDER DATE:  Jan 28, 2021
SIZE: 43 pounds
APPROXIMATE AGE: 10 months
SHELTER STAFF SAYS:  Are looking for a fun ball of fluff to join your family? Our little buddy Dodge is ready to fill that spot! Dodge was a little nervous when he first came to us, but with the help of yummy treats and our love and affection, he came around rather quickly. Dodge loves to romp and play in the yard, snuggle up for belly rubs, and eat the tastiest treats! He is learning how to walk well on the leash and will need a little potty training. But one look in those sweet eyes and you will know every moment is worth it! So come on out and meet Dodge today and you won't be able to leave without him!

Due to Covid, we now work by appointment only and work on a first come basis.  If you are interested in making an appointment, please call the HCHS at 512-793-5463.  You can see all our available animals at HillCountryHumaneSociety.org.
All our adoptable dogs are treated for fleas, given DHPPV and Bordatella vaccines and are de-wormed.  
When you adopt one of our animals it will be micro chipped and registered at the time of adoption.  Also, if not already altered, you will receive a voucher to get your animal spay/neutered.
While we do our best to determine the breeds of our dogs, the majority are strays, and we have only general appearance, coat type, size, ear type, tail, tongue color and coat color to base breed on.  It is always possible when adopting a puppy that it will change dramatically to look like another breed.

animal.description:
Pennie is an estimated 9.5 year old spayed female Terrier mix.
She is looking for an experienced dog owner, who needs a devoted companion. 
Pennie is an indoor dog, and cannot be left outside for long amounts of time or she will bark, especially if neighbor dogs are there to give her something to bark at. 
Pennie is very people oriented, and likes to be near you whenever possible. 
She can live in a home with other pets, HOWEVER she is very dominant, and is food aggressive with other animals. 
Therefore she would need to be fed separately, and not be able to access food freely. 
Feeding her in a kennel or a separate room from other pets would be good options. 

Pennie takes a minute to warm up to unfamiliar animals, and she prefers pets that give her space and don’t overwhelm her, low energy, well balanced dogs would be best.

Pennie prefers children old enough to know to stay out of her face, she doesn’t like to be poked in the face, and while very tolerant and friendly overall with people, she would prefer a home without small children. 

Pennie has very manageable energy levels. 
A short walk, or some playtime in the yard with you, and she is calm and happy. 

She is housetrained, and Microchipped. 
 

If you are interested in this animal,
Please Call us at 435-723-1231 during business hours, we only have one Shelter Technician, so if your phone call is not answered, Leave us a message and we will call you back!

Our Business hours are Tuesday-Friday 10AM-6PM
And Saturday from 9AM-12PM
Or email us at brighamcityanimalshelter@gmail.com anytime.

We are located at 1220 West Forest Street, Brigham City UT, 84302


We are Rescue friendly!
If you are part of a 501C3 Non Profit Organization and would like to Rescue an animal from us if not adopted, PLEASE CONTACT US!

animal.description: Sweet dog, would be good for a senior or adult home. NO small children please. He is a senior dog, but still has energy for a good walk around the block daily. Can be vocal, may not do well in an apartment with thin walls as he howls due to seperation anxiety. He was left in our parking lot and surprisingly was not claimed by an owner. He had severe dental disease upon arrival but our Vet staff cleaned and extracted what they could. He will need regular senior dog check ups with a Vet to keep his teeth/gums healthy as well as his body. Senior dogs need to visit a Vet more often than a younger dog, so please make sure this is in your budget. He was adopted since the last statement but unfortunately, was not taken care off as he should have been and was luckily returned to us. He is not a dog to be left outside, he is an inside, lap dog that is very smart if you take the time to pay attention to the signs he gives you. He will whine and walk around rapidly if he has to go outside to do his business. He will also need regular grooming so his hair isn't left to mat up and be painful. He seems to like other dogs, but a meet and greet with your dog is must before adoption. If you are interested, please submit an application and then make an appointment on burbankanimalshelter.org

animal.description: Woof, woof! I'm so excited you're thinking about adopting a new fur-ever family member! Here are a few things that may help you with your big decision. First, dogs just want to be happy and feel loved. Living inside and being a part of the family is really important to us. A lot of the things you need as humans to stay happy and healthy, us dogs need too. We depend on you for things like vet visits, nutritious food, clean water, social and play time with people and other pets, training classes, toys, and of course, lots of love and attention! Regular baths, nail trims and grooming help us to look and feel our best, while monthly flea and heartworm prevention help us to stay healthy. Did you know that depending on our size and breed, dogs can live up to 20 years? Just think of the wonderful life we could have together!

animal.description: Mojo is a very playful and energetic dog who really enjoys the company of people. He can get a bit uncomfortable when being handled and is not especially fond of hugs, but he is eager to recieve affection with petting and scratching. Though he is already 2 years old, he still gives off major puppy energy and could definitely use more training. He already knows sit and shake so he is not a stranger to learning new commands. Mojo can get rowdy, especially during play, and needs to learn that a dog his size should not jump on people too much. For this reason, we recommend that Mojo goes to a home with teens and/or adults, where there aren't tiny humans he can knock over. Mojo is also working on his confidence around other dogs. He tends to become frustrated or fearful, so we strongly recommend that his new family have previous large dog experience. Any dogs in the home should come down and meet him. We do not currently know how he would do with cats.

animal.description: Sauro is an 11 year old former international champion show dog whose owner passed away and whose family surrendered him to a high kill shelter where we immediately were called upon to help with his rescue. This English Cocker boy is now safe with us and we will ensure that he lives out the remainder of his life in a loving and caring home that will not only love him for his beauty but also for his devotion and gentle spirit. Sauro is deaf and may have some minor vision impairment as well but he can get around just fine - just no homes with unfenced swimming pools - we will err on the side of caution on this. Also we will require a home where there are no small children- this kind soul deserves to be treated with dignity and small children can sometimes alarm and manhandle dogs- we do not want that for him and will not make any exceptions. Sauro does get along well with other dogs and cats , but mostly what he enjoys is a soft dog bed or blanket by the side of his foster mom where he can rest and watch the "world" from the comfort of a safe place. If interested in adopting Sauro please fill out an application at www.floridacockerrescue.org ADOPTION FEE: $275.00

**WE ARE ALWAYS IN NEED OF FOSTER HOMES**  Homeward Bound Dog Rescue is an all volunteer rescue organization and all our dogs and puppies are in foster homes - we are not a shelter and do NOT have a facility where we house our dogs. For adoption information go to: www.homewardbounddogrescue.com.  You must fill out an application online as we do NOT accept applications at our clinics.

Hi there, I am Dash, a male Catahoula mix, 1 year old and 35 lb. I came to the shelter as a stray. I am young and happy and very friendly. I love people and I am good with other dogs and cats. I love toys, especially ones that make noise. I am also very good at tug a war.


We are presently not holding our regular Saturday adoption clinics due to the Covid-19 virus.  We are operating on a limited basis until further notice, but we are still adopting dogs out. We require an approved application before we consider anyone for an adoption - so filling out the application is your first step.   Different dogs and puppies go up for adoption EVERY WEEK so please feel free to visit the site and click on the Petfinder link for updates. Puppies and dogs up to 2 years old are $350. Dogs over 2 years old are $250. 100% of the adoption fees go to help us save more dogs.

animal.description:
Mercury is a 5 year old German Shepherd mix (~65lbs) and has the softest ears. Mercury is people and dog friendly. He's more 'dog ambivalent.' At the dog park he gets along with other dogs, and is especially interested in smaller dogs. However, he mainly uses the dog park as a chance to go around to the other pet parents and collect head scratches. Mercury loves all people (male, female, kids and adults). He is especially good with little kids and sits very patiently as they pet him (or treat him like a drum, which has happened).

This sweet boy is low-energy, and his preferred method of working out is moving from one comfy couch and dog bed to another. He does like to go with you to the park on short walks, especially if the park has super plush grass. Rolling around in the grass is his favorite (as is attracting an audience of people to pet him). 

Mercury is the lowest maintenance dog his foster mom has ever had. He is house-trained. He is fine alone during the day out of his kennel, and is the only dog not to chew anything, ever. He particularly enjoys Gordan Ramsey shows (likely for the food on screen). He's not into toys, unless they're toys that have treats hidden inside. He loves food and is slowly putting on weight after a rough life. 

Mercury is looking for his forever home with lots of belly scratches, and lots of treats.

animal.description:
Ice is such a sweet boy! He's friendly with strangers and shares his tail wags with everyone. He is house broken and likes his walks. He loves to find the warmest, coziest place in the house and settle in for naps, and he'll never turn down a chance for scratches and pets! He's happy to lounge in the same room while you work or do his own thing if you're out. 

He has met other larger dogs and was NOT nice (snarling and growling). He's also been barking at lone strangers on our walks. Honestly, it seems like pretty typical chihuahua/small dog behavior, but I think it might be an indicator that he'll need slow introductions to any dogs or strangers outside of the home. 

Also, we discovered he has no bottom teeth in the front of his mouth! The missing teeth doesn't seem to be cause any issues. 

Ice is a well adjusted pup who just needs a day or two to get used to his new surroundings and he will make a great addition to any family!

animal.description:
Kate is an extremely loving and quiet dog. She seeks touching, petting, and cuddling and would be a great family pet. She is very tame and kind.

She is potty trained but not used to a kennel. She sleeps on her foster's bed. When left alone for a few hours, she sleeps on the bed and there is no mess. She patiently waits for the foster's return.

Kate doesn't have a strong command knowledge but would learn very fast. She sort of understands but is still nervous. She stays, but temporarily because she wants to be with you. She responds to come. She has limited success with sit and down. She seems good with hand commands and body language. She is smart and simply needs guidance. The basics are there, and she needs someone to spend time with her (which she would like). She's very trainable.

Kate walks extremely well. She doesn't pull and comes when you tell her to move on. She stays close beside you. 

She doesn't get aggressive around people or other animals, though she has not been close to other dogs. She doesn't seem agitated at all around them when she sees them. Even when they bark at her. She just looks at them and stays close (but not in a scared way). The only time she reacted was when she wanted to chase a squirrel. She will kind of growl when she sees similar pit bull type dog. 

She would love a backyard but is quiet and might work well in an apartment too.She is a very quiet dog and rarely barks. She does have a soft/gentle whine to get your attention once in a while. She wants love.

Kate is an amazing companion. She wants to be sit beside and mostly on you on couch. Wants to be petted, scratched. She doesn't like to play (yet), but with love and trust, she may learn.

animal.description:
For my Petfinder.com friends, please contact the Shelter at (248) 858-1070 for more information. My ID number is 336940

I am available for adoption; however due to my breed my adoption will have to be facilitated through a rescue organization. Please see the front desk staff or contact the Shelter at (248) 858-1070 for more information.

Meet Amelia Braveheart! Isn't she beautiful? Amelia is a super sweet girl, who is excited about life and people! When she first entered the Shelter, she was a bit shy, but she has come to learn that the staff are friends, that give her treats and lots of attention! Amelia did well when meeting her canine shelter friends, although a bit shy with the females. This girl is eager to please and wants nothing more than to be apart of a family, where she can be included in all that is going on! She deserves a loving home, one where she is well cared for!

The following descriptions describe behaviors that were observed during testing and/or veterinary examination: Evaluated for temperament with 336798 (female), and 336985 (male). Did very well with male, she was a bit intimidated/unsure with female. Needs confidence building. Loves to play 1/27/2021

American Pit Bulls are a misunderstood breed; for this reason, we implore adopters to these beautiful dogs to be very vigilant in training and socialization. This breed is very energetic and will need daily exercise. Because of their strength and energy, apartment living may not be the best fit. This breed can be loving, loyal and very smart. 

The above behaviors and personality traits have been observed while at the Shelter. If this animal was relinquished, information is gathered from the owner regarding behavior. Our wonderful volunteers spend time with these animals and give input on behaviors and traits. However, this description may not be all inclusive to how this animal will act in a loving forever home. Introduction to established family pets should be slow and monitored always. The same goes for children and other family members. Adopting a pet is a big decision and should be thoughtful. We suggest researching different breeds to match traits and personalities to your lifestyle. When adopting a pet, please know that this pet will be with you for their lifetime; patience and consistency will make for a successful adoption.

animal.description:
A PUPPY-SIZED BUNDLE OF HAPPINESS!

THE BASICS:

Beagle mix; brown and white
ADULT FEMALE; EST DOB: 2019
ARRIVAL: January 16, 2021
HISTORY:  Beans was found as a stray in the middle of the road.

What an adorable girl!  Beans is currently the smallest dog at CFC, and though she is the size of a puppy, we believe that she is full-grown.  Since she’s arrived here, Beans’ tail has rarely stopped wagging.  She loves to meet people and can often be seen standing on her hind legs against the fence in an attempt to get your attention.  She loves exploring new places with her nose to the ground and tail to the sky.  We’ve also found her to be really smart!  If you hold your fist over her head, Beans will stand up.  We’re not sure if this was a trick she was taught at some point or if she just likes to stand, but we think it’s cool either way.  Given her intelligence, curiosity, and small size, Beans can be a bit of an escape artist.  Make sure there aren’t any cracks big enough for her to squeeze through!  Beans doesn’t mind being held but prefers to keep her feet on the ground.  She’s pretty uninterested in most toys and would rather run around with you than chase a ball.  Overall, Beans is a cheerful, loving dog that we feel will adapt quickly to living with a family of her own.

animal.description:
ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS
Fenced yard
Canine sibling if not adopted together

My name is Misty. I am the Chihuahua mix. I am about 6 months old. My sissy is Layla. She is a Dachshund mix and she is about a year old.

We have become the best of friends in our foster home and our foster mom would like to keep us together if at all possible. We are both crate trained and sleep in it together. We play together non stop. Layla likes to sleep next to our foster mom at night and I sleep next to her. We are both working on being housebroken. I am just a baby so I'm still learning. Layla was turned in to an outside dog shortly after she was adopted so she never really had to learn where to go. Our foster mom found out and went and got her. That's not allowed here. We are good with other dogs and with kids. I have to eat in my own crate though because I am very possessive of my food. I weigh about 7lbs and Layal weighs about 12lbs. We would be most grateful if you would consider giving us both a home together. Our foster mom said she won't separate us unless it's absolutely necessary.

If you would like to meet Misty and Layla send us an email to theloveofk9s@yahoo.com and we will get back with you as soon as we can.

Adoption donations pays for all vetting for both girls...spays, heart worm tests, all vaccinations, deworming, flea prevention, microchips and wellness exams

animal.description:
Jazzy is an 8-year-old mixed breed rescued from a high-kill shelter. This dog is current on vaccinations, microchipped, 4dx/heartworm tested, and spayed. This dog is also tested with other dogs, kennel-trained, and housebroken. We would love for you to meet this dog and see if it might be a good fit for your home. 

The first step to adoption is completing an adoption application on our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org. Pending approval, your application is valid for 1 year, and you will be eligible to request a hold on an individual animal. The hold does not require that you adopt the animal, but ensures you get to meet and make an adoption decision prior to other applicants. Hold times cannot exceed 5 days. Also pending approval, you will be able to acquire foster home contact information, so you inquire on personalities of specific animals.

***COVID-19 Update: While we typically host weekly Saturday adoption events, in order to follow the CDC's recommendation for COVID-19 protocols, we will be suspending our weekly Saturday adoption events until given the clear. Adoptions for individual animals will occur by private adoption appointment and/or adoption handoff. Appointments and handoffs are scheduled pending staff, foster home, and vetting schedules. Because we are 100% foster-based, adoption appointments and handoffs are only offered for individual animals. When adopting at an appointment, please be aware that you will be taking the animal home that day. We can not hold animals to be picked up at a later date.

Due to CDC's recommended COVID-19 protocols, we are highly encouraging foster homes and adopters to speak with one another via phone or video chat to ensure compatible matches and limit in-person contact. If meeting in person, our foster homes are encouraged to wear masks, socially distance, and choose an outdoor meeting spot. Should you want to proceed forward with the adoption, all adoption paperwork, medical records, and adoption fees are to be completed electronically. Quick and low-contact animal handoff is also being encouraged amongst foster homes and adopters. As always, we include a one-week trial period with all our adoptions. ***

Please note, we do not have the ability to process adoption applications at our adoption events, so please plan accordingly. If an application is submitted past 5pm on Monday-Thursday, it will begin review the following day. If submitted on Friday-Sunday, it will begin review on Monday. It takes approximately 48-72 hours for an application to be processed.

For additional questions regarding meeting this dog please contact us via text/email at 970.699.6772, or contact@bounceanimalrescue.org. We apologize for any inconvenience, but due to a high volume of inquiries, calls and voicemails regarding adoption will not be returned.

Thank you for choosing adoption! If you would like more information on our organization please visit our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org.

Any other specifics:  Chico is an adorable litttle speedy gonzalez pup with an appetite for life! He is great with other dogs and ignores cats. However, he will chase and try to eat chickens. Chico is good with children, though he does try to jump up and give everyone he knows and meets hugs and kisses. 
Chico loves playing with other dogs, so he would do well in a home with dogs or having pup playdates. He does gaurd his food and toys from other dogs, however. So it's important to know that he needs to be fed and given chew toys separate from other animals. He has NOT shown guarding issues towards people. In fact his foster parents normally play with his bone and pet him while he eats without any issues. 
Chico may not be the best apartment dog unless his person tends to do 2 to 3 walks or runs with him per day. He can be a very cuddly couch potato at times, but is definitely ready to go go go a fair amount of the day. 

Chico is fully crate trained and house trained, however he is crated when unsupervised to avoid any unwanted chewing or accidents since he is still just a teen pup. 

Will you be a Hero in Chico's story?

Visit our website/Click on Adopt to APPLY today!  RARErescue.org

Adoption Fee: $225.00



PLEASE NOTE: We are a non-profit organization without municipal or government funding. Veterinary/Medical expenses are constant for an animal rescue. Our adoption fees not only help to provide vetting and care for the animal being adopted, but they also help to cover heartworm treatments and other treatable ailments that many animals, that would otherwise be euthanized, need in order to be made available for adoption.



Please understand that adopting an animal is a LIFETIME COMMITMENT to that animal and there will be veterinary expenses throughout their life that can often cost several hundreds, if not thousands of dollars (without pet insurance), especially without annual checkups and preventative care.  As a potential family for this pet you are responsible for their safety and that includes keeping them on your property.

***If you are not in the middle Tennessee area, transport can potentially be arranged to approved homes, depending on distance and local adaptability. We normally do not allow adoptions outside of 1.5 hours driving distance.

Thank you for choosing to adopt, foster, or aid in the rescue efforts of RARE!

animal.description:
A FUN & ACTIVE YOUNG FELLOW:  10 months old / Currently 35 lbs. 

Hello, I’m Finn!  I had a home, but my family was not able to give me the exercise I needed to be a happy pup, so Mostly Mutts is helping me find a new family to love!  

• OTHER DOGS/CATS/KIDS:  I came in with another dog, and we get along well, though our play can be a little rough together.  I also met other dogs at MM’s and liked them, so if you have a dog at home already, let’s meet / Cats unknown / I haven’t met kids yet at Mostly Mutts.  My former family suggests older kids, as I may bump over smaller children with my enthusiasm and higher energy level.

• PERSONALITY/ENERGY LEVEL:  I am a sweet guy with a ‘big dog look’ in a compact body.  I am playful and loving, though I can be a bit hand shy and skittish with new people initially.  The MM volunteers say that I am a great dog and I like that / My energy level is 6-8, so I look forward to lots of regular opportunities to exercise in my new home.   

• SKILLS/CRATE/POTTY:  I am now a student in the Mostly Mutts University training program, where I am learning lots of great doggie commands with my trainer.  I have mastered ‘sit’ (and love to do it!), ‘down’, ‘come’, ‘drop-it’, ‘place’ and I’m working on good leash manners (we are working on my zig zagging and pulling) / My crate manners are good at Mostly Mutts and my former owner also said they were good / My potty habits have been good at Mostly Mutts, and my previous owner reported that I have good potty habits, also.

• LIKES/DISLIKES:  I love to play, and I enjoy going to the Mostly Mutts yard play pen for a nice game of fetch, and a soccer type game with a very large ball.  A fenced yard where we can play could be nice in my new home / I can’t think of any dislikes, but I would not be happy if I did not get the exercise, love, exercise, training and attention on which I thrive!    

• MEDICAL:   I'm current on vaccinations, micro-chipped and neutered.

I am looking for a fun family to give me a great home and love me furever!  My adoption fee is $299.00, and I’m located in Kennesaw, Ga.

Hi..I am Joey. I am a Boxer mix that's in the market for a new home. I am about a year old and weigh 61lbs. My foster mom says I am a very good boy and she's only has me a few days!! She thinks I was allowed to take people food from the littles in my former home because I think your plate is my plate. I am learning really quick that's not the case!! I am a little bossy with my food so I eat away from my foster siblings. I go nuts when I see a leash because I love going for walks and car rides. I am housebroken and crate trained. I just need some training in the manners area because no one ever worked with me and I am like a big puppy. I am also a huge snuggler and I am all about the belly rubs. I am good with kids and other dogs so far but I'm not sure about those things called cats because I haven't been around them since coming here. I would be fine as an only dog as long as my humans are active and keep my busy

If you would like to meet Joey send us an email to theloveofk9s@yahoo.com and we will get back with you as quick as we can.

Adoption donation pays for all vetting...my neuter, a heart worm test, all vaccinations, deworming, flea prevention, a microchip and a wellness exam.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Odin is a large, 4 year old neutered male Great Pyrenees currently living in a somewhat rural neighborhood with his family. He LOVES long walks off leash, chasing squirrels, eating snacks, snuggling with his cats, protecting his yard and lounging with his family. He can be playful for short bursts of time but generally prefers loafing around.

Odin has excellent manners on a leash when people and dogs give him a wide berth on the trail. He is sensitive and smart and responds well to positive reinforcement. He has become increasingly protective of his people and property and would likely make a good livestock or property guarding dog with some training. Odin has lived with other Pyrs successfully and generally ignores other dogs when at a kennel. He needs to develop social skills when meeting new dogs and would benefit from someone with experience doing so.

He initially enjoyed meeting new people when he arrived to his family, but over time his strongly protective nature has emerged and he now tries to guard his family from others and does not want new people close by. When in situations where he does not need to guard his people or property, such as when he stays at the kennel overnight, he does not exhibit his guarding tendencies and is fairly easy-going with other people and dogs. UPS trucks are his nemesis and he needs to be leashed or in a sturdily fenced yard when they are around.

His ideal day would be roaming his property during the day, protecting his people and property, and spending the nights inside with his people and cozy bed.

If you are interested in Odin, please fill out our Adoption Application (transport can be arranged!).

I am 42 lbs., 3 years old, and l am looking for my forever home.

Adoption Donation: $450

All dogs are microchipped, neutered, current on all vaccines, heartworm tested and started on Tri Heart Plus; Vectra 3D.

All household members and any dogs from the household need to be present at the time of the adoption.

Our website is always kept 100% up to date with who is currently available.  As soon as animals are adopted, they are moved to the Adopted Pets page so if they are still listed on the Adoptable Dogs or Cats page, they are still available. So keep any eye on the site for any animals being added as available for adoption as new animals are added everyday! We would recommend if you haven’t done so already that you submit a general online adoption application with us so it is on file for when you are ready to come out and adopt. The adoption counselors will be able to show you many that would be a good fit for your family. Animal House Shelter can not guarantee breed or breed mix of our adoptable animals. The animals are posted on the website as a breed or breed mix based on their physical characteristics they most resemble. We also can not guarantee the ages of our adoptable animals or how large puppies will be when fully grown.

Please fill out an online adoption application. Visit our 'Adopt' page to view adoption process steps, policies, requirements and FAQ. View our 'Visit' page for hours and directions to our shelter. We look forward to seeing you soon!

animal.description:
MY STORY: Chance came to CBHS as an owner surrender due to moving to a location that did not allow animals. 

AGE: Approximately 3 years.

TRICKS & COMMANDS: Sit, Shake.

ABOUT CHANCE: How could you ever say no to those eyes?! Chance is a happy-go-lucky boy who always has a big smile on his face.

Chance can be a little slow to trust new people that he meets but once he warms up he won't leave your side. Although he can be vocal at times, his tail never stops wagging and he calms down easily once you show him that you're listening. Chance loves any type of treats that you have for him!

While he loves being pet and getting belly rubs all day, Chance has told us that he would love a home with older children that know to respect his boundaries. Chance also gets excited and plays well when other doggy friends are around.

Adoption fee includes spay/neuter, vaccinations, worming, microchip, and a start on flea/tick prevention.

For more information, please call CBHS adoptions at 319-232-6887 or email at adoptioncounselor@yahoo.com.

animal.description: Hi, how are you? I'm Dandy! Get it? People might say I'm reserved and bashful with some new people, but to my family I'm just a big lovable lug! I can be hesitant with people I don't know and men in particular, so I'm more of a homebody than social butterfly. Since I get a tad nervous with noises and meeting new people, I'm not suitable for an apartment setting. Instead, I need a low-traffic home without frequent visitors and where any children are closer to their teens. I also will need to be the only male dog in my new home. I would like to meet all family members, including any resident dogs, to make sure we're a perfect match! Dandy is a Diamond Dog and will be shown by appointment only. Diamond Dogs are dogs that are currently receiving special training from staff and volunteers through our behavior modification program. If you are interested in learning more about this animal, please fill out an application by clicking here . Be sure to include Dandy A1286516 when filling out the survey. After reviewing your application, we will only be reaching out to you if the animal is a good fit for your home.

animal.description: Romeo is a 2 year old 40lb male American Pit Bull Terrier Mix. He came to us as a stray, so we do not have any background information on him. He has energy to spare and LOVES attention. He's very friendly here at the shelter. He has had a positive interaction with another dog here at the shelter. He is heartworm positive. This is a curable condition and cannot be passed directly to other animals. He qualified for a 30% off voucher through our Have-A-Heart program. We are open by appointment only to ensure we can properly social distance here at the shelter. We cannot guarantee a specific pet or type of pet will be available at your appointment. We do not hold pets. We operate on a first come first serve basis and while you can put what/who you are interested in in the appointment sign up, all appointments are general dog/cat/other animal appointments since we cannot guarantee what will be available at the time of your appointment. If you would like to set up a non-specific dog or cat appointment we have our scheduling system online now at: https://guilfordcountync.gov/our-county/animal-services/animal-shelter/animal-adoption-scheduling All adopted cats and dogs at Guilford County Animal Services come fully up to date on age appropriate vaccines, spayed/neutered, and microchipped. If you are interested in meeting any of our pets, please visit our website to schedule an appointment online. If you believe this may be your pet, please come to the shelter during business hours and bring your ID, proof of ownership, and proof of spay/neuter and/or rabies vaccination history if you have it. See our reclaiming your pet page for more information.
animal.name: ROMEO

animal.description:
38 Special once passionately sung that a heart needs a second chance... we say that this Chance needs a heart to take him in and give him a loving home. At only a year and a half, Chance has not had the opportunity to thrive. He lived with owners who used to let him and his sister run the streets and didn't teach him any manners.  

We have worked with Chance, and he now walks pretty well on a leash, and learning commands.  Chance is very energetic, smart, trainable, and loving.  He really enjoys human interaction and is quite affectionate.  Chance would do best with an active owner who can give him the exercise and stimulation he needs.  He does need to be an only pet and in a home without young children.   

Upon adoption, we will cover two training sessions with trainer Katie Gallagher, from Kate's K-9's.

animal.description: This handsome guy is named Bandit and he is looking for a new forever home! Bandit arrived at the shelter as a stray and we weren't able to get in touch with his family. Bandit came in with some hair loss but he is on the mend and doesn't need anything other than some soothing baths, good food, love, and time to heal up! Bandit weighs about 56 pounds and he has been fully vetted. Since he was a stray we don't know much about his background or how he does with kids, other dogs, or cats. Bandit is a little bit shy when he first meets people but if you have a ball to play with he will become your friend in no time at all! Bandit LOVES to play fetch and is hoping to find a human that is ready to play fetch endlessly, go for long walks or hikes, and provide plenty of tennis balls in the house to keep him happy! ,Due to COVID-19, all adoptions will be by appointment only. To adopt, complete our online adoption application and an Adoption Counselor will contact you within 48-hours to schedule your adoption appointment. Adoptions for any pets in foster will be completed offsite at our PetSmart Claiborne location on a case by case basis. The safety of our foster parents and community is of utmost importance to us and it will be at the foster's discretion if they'd like to meet at this time. Thank you for choosing adoption! 

Okay, everything about Sugar is wonderful.  She is sweet and easy going, interested in befriending dogs and people she meets, and just plain happy.  This is a great dog; she walks nicely on the leash and gently takes treats.  She likes plush toys.  You are going to love this dog. She even spent some time in a foster home getting a head start on her training! Sugar is an Underdog because despite everything you've just read, she has yet to find her forever home! We want our Underdogs to win, so we reduced her fee to $25! To meet Sugar please make an adoption appointment at our New Orleans Campus.

To inquire about an adoptable animal from the Louisiana SPCA, please call 504.368.5191, ext. 150 to speak with an adoption counselor.
To see more adoptable animals from the Louisiana SPCA, please go to http://la-spca.org/adopt.



The petfinder.com system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our dogs. Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Curry and her siblings were surrendered to us via some fellow rescuers who are working hard to rectify a hoarding situation. We are so thankful for their work and excited to find these deserving babies' forever families!

Curry came to us at 8 weeks old and, thankfully, it's clear this Chihuahua family was treated well and had lots of positive experiences with both dogs and humans during their first 8 weeks of life. These babies are friendly and affectionate, eager to please and feisty, energetic and very playful. They race around at top speeds, bouncing and running and hopping and romping, for an hour and then they crawl and collapse, exhausted, into their crates. These puppies are spunky, and mouthy, and full of sass. They also love to cuddle, chew bones and antlers, and nap! They are NOT potty trained and will require lots of continued training in their forever homes including crate, house and potty training, and lots of continued responsible socialization.

We do not know the parents of these puppies, therefore, we cannot be sure how large they will be in adulthood. Best guess is that they will be 8-12 pounds, perhaps as large as 15. If small size is important to you, this is not the litter for you. These puppies would love a house with a yard, and a doggie playmate or two. Because they are puppies, they'll be fine with dog-savvy cats and respectful children old enough to have impulse control.

Please note: socializing dogs, especially young dogs, is critical to their development. Puppies need to have positive experiences with new people, places, sounds, dogs on a WEEKLY basis to ensure they do not grow into insecure, fearful or even aggressive adult dogs. Please consider this when adopting during this pandemic. Socialization is currently more difficult, but it isn't any less important, so please be sure you can fulfill this need in a new dog before committing to adopt.

If you are interested in adopting, please complete an adoption application. Because we are still understaffed due to COVID19, we will only be able to email those applicants that are approved to schedule a meet and greet. Thank you in advance for your understanding if you don't hear back from us regarding your application.

Hello, let’s talk.  My name is Kane & yours is?  I am as sweet as ‘sugar’, 1.5 - 2 years old, a true petite girl at just 30lbs - like the old saying goes ‘good things come is small packages’!  I am playful outside, love to run - quick like a bunny.  I am not a ‘toy’ player but love your company and other humans & fur kids.  Inside, I get 4 stars for incredible house manners.  I would not be your ‘alert’ dog because I want nothing to do with chaos or any commotion. I prefer to zoom down into the bedroom, hop up on the bed, and snuggle against the pillow.  I love to snuggle with you but truly on my own time.  I am very sensitive to quick movement & strange sounds.  I do regain my confidence fairly quickly but do not like to be ‘pushed’.  I like my pace & I’m sticking with it!  :-) When outside, I will alert you to something but not by barking - I prefer to just stand at attention. Walking on leash and riding in a vehicle are ok by me - a little hesitant loading, my recall is outstanding, I know & love my name.  I am living in Mesa with other dogs & we all get along marvelously! I would be best suited in a home w/out young children’. ‘Quick movements & strange sounds scare me and send me running!

Happy Tails Adoption Center is open on Sundays from 12-5pm. We are located at 7940 University Ave NE, Fridley. Dogs are at events based on the availability of their foster family. Because their breed mix is a guess we cannot guarantee a 'full grown size' of many of our younger animals.Interested in adopting me? If there is a certain animal you want to meet at one the events please fill out a preadoption application to directly contact their foster family or check our Facebook page to see if they will be there! Their event attendance is based on the availability of their foster family.
